Date:8/15/2007 7:11:17 AM
From:RockyBalboa
Back of the envelope calculus shows that like others TMA uses a leverage of
about 21x and has a balance sheet of nearly 54B in bonds. After the write off,
the leverage reaches nearly LTCMish 30x.

If they write down their book by 26% (from 19.38 to 14.28) then they marked
down their portfolio overall by 1.17%.
This doesn't sound very much of a revaluation, except if they have the best
rated pieces of MBS which in turn have the best underlying assets. In this
case, one percent is a lot.
If they had worse tranches then they would likely not survive.

In absolute terms the liquidity amounts or potential margin calls are still
staggering.
a 1.2% loss in equity would mean that equity was reduced by 630MM.
It also means that lenders would require significant liquidity if they asked
TMA to post required cash margin to a level that a certain lower leverage or
coverage is restored.
I have no idea how much lenders would require from TMA.
