AP
KKR Sells $5.1 Billion Mortgage Loans
Wednesday August 15, 9:17 am ET
KKR Records $40 Million Loss to Sell Off Nearly Half of Its Residential
Mortgage Portfolio

SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Specialty finance firm KKR Financial Holdings LLC said
Wednesday it sold about $5.1 billion in residential mortgage loans as it
continues to divest residential real estate assets.

The sale of the mortgages and related interest rate swaps held for hedging
purposes will result in a $40 million loss for KKR.

KKR Financial operated as a real estate investment trust until May 2007, which
required it to derive at least 75 percent of the company's gross income from
real estate assets. Since transforming to a limited liability company, KKR has
moved to divest itself of all residential mortgage holdings.

KKR still owns about $5.8 billion in mortgage loans, most of which are held as
mortgage-backed securities. KKR will continue to sell off its mortgage
portfolio while also allowing some of the loans to come off the books through
regular principal payments.

Investors have been shying away from mortgages in recent months as delinquency
and default rates rise, especially among subprime loans -- mortgages given to
customers with poor credit history. Dozens of mortgage lenders, including some
that operated as real estate investment trusts, have gone out of business as
liquidity in the market has disappeared.

